  "preview": "One challenging thing in business is explaining something your stakeholders have never actually experienced",
  "text": "𝗢𝗻𝗲 𝗰𝗵𝗮𝗹𝗹𝗲𝗻𝗴𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝘁𝗵𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝗶𝗻 𝗯𝘂𝘀𝗶𝗻𝗲𝘀𝘀 𝗶𝘀 𝗲𝘅𝗽𝗹𝗮𝗶𝗻𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝘀𝗼𝗺𝗲𝘁𝗵𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝘆𝗼𝘂𝗿 𝘀𝘁𝗮𝗸𝗲𝗵𝗼𝗹𝗱𝗲𝗿𝘀 𝗵𝗮𝘃𝗲 𝗻𝗲𝘃𝗲𝗿 𝗮𝗰𝘁𝘂𝗮𝗹𝗹𝘆 𝗲𝘅𝗽𝗲𝗿𝗶𝗲𝗻𝗰𝗲𝗱 — like self-organization or culture in action.\n\nHow do you explain something that doesn't exist in someone's world? 🤔\n\nHow do you explain trees to someone from the Greenland tundra, where trees don’t grow for thousands of miles around?\nMissionaries explaining the Bible to Innuits must have struggled with this — the text mentions dozens of different trees: cedars, oaks, figs, palms…\n\nAt the beginning of my leadership career, I read about team dynamics — the classic stages: storming, norming, performing.\nOn paper, it all made perfect sense. And we were in the performing phase.\n\nUntil one day I realized: wait — we’re actually in the storming phase.\nWhat I thought had been well explained to me turned out to be theoretical — until I lived through the full cycle in an actual team.✅\n\n𝘚𝘰 𝘵𝘩𝘪𝘴 𝘪𝘴 𝘸𝘩𝘢𝘵 𝘵𝘩𝘦 “𝘴𝘵𝘰𝘳𝘮𝘪𝘯𝘨 𝘴𝘵𝘢𝘨𝘦” 𝘳𝘦𝘢𝘭𝘭𝘺 𝘭𝘰𝘰𝘬𝘴 𝘭𝘪𝘬𝘦 🙂 𝘞𝘰𝘰𝘰𝘰𝘰𝘸!\n\nThe explanation gave me a glimpse of understanding.\n𝗢𝗻𝗹𝘆 𝗿𝗲𝗮𝗹 𝗲𝘅𝗽𝗲𝗿𝗶𝗲𝗻𝗰𝗲 𝘃𝗮𝗹𝗶𝗱𝗮𝘁𝗲𝗱 𝗶𝘁 𝗮𝗻𝗱 𝗺𝗮𝗱𝗲 𝗶𝘁 𝗿𝗲𝗮𝗹.\n\nSame thing with company culture.\nAt Speed and Function we state that we strive for 𝗮 𝗯𝗹𝗮𝗺𝗲𝗹𝗲𝘀𝘀 𝗰𝘂𝗹𝘁𝘂𝗿𝗲.\nDuring interviews, some employees say they already work in a blameless environment and know exactly what that means.\n\nSix months later, after working at S&F:\n“𝘖𝘩… 𝘸𝘩𝘢𝘵 𝘐 𝘩𝘢𝘥 𝘣𝘦𝘧𝘰𝘳𝘦 𝘸𝘢𝘴 𝘢𝘤𝘵𝘶𝘢𝘭𝘭𝘺 𝘲𝘶𝘪𝘵𝘦 𝘣𝘭𝘢𝘮𝘦𝘧𝘶𝘭.”\n\nWe had a client who started with:\n“𝘞𝘩𝘺 𝘥𝘰 𝘸𝘦 𝘯𝘦𝘦𝘥 𝘢 𝘴𝘦𝘭𝘧-𝘰𝘳𝘨𝘢𝘯𝘪𝘻𝘦𝘥 𝘤𝘶𝘭𝘵𝘶𝘳𝘦? 𝘐𝘵 𝘥𝘰𝘦𝘴𝘯’𝘵 𝘸𝘰𝘳𝘬 𝘧𝘰𝘳 𝘶𝘴.”\nAnd ended with:\n“𝘐’𝘷𝘦 𝘳𝘦𝘢𝘭𝘭𝘺 𝘢𝘱𝘱𝘳𝘦𝘤𝘪𝘢𝘵𝘦𝘥 𝘵𝘩𝘦 𝘧𝘦𝘦𝘥𝘣𝘢𝘤𝘬 𝘤𝘶𝘭𝘵𝘶𝘳𝘦. 𝘐 𝘧𝘦𝘦𝘭 𝘭𝘪𝘬𝘦 𝘐’𝘮 𝘣𝘦𝘪𝘯𝘨 𝘭𝘪𝘴𝘵𝘦𝘯𝘦𝘥 𝘵𝘰 — 𝘢𝘯𝘥 𝘪𝘵’𝘴 𝘤𝘰𝘮𝘪𝘯𝘨 𝘧𝘳𝘰𝘮 𝘢 𝘱𝘭𝘢𝘤𝘦 𝘰𝘧 𝘨𝘳𝘰𝘸𝘵𝘩, 𝘯𝘰𝘵 𝘫𝘶𝘥𝘨𝘮𝘦𝘯𝘵. 𝘞𝘦 𝘯𝘰𝘸 𝘸𝘢𝘯𝘵 𝘰𝘶𝘳 𝘪𝘯𝘵𝘦𝘳𝘯𝘢𝘭 𝘵𝘦𝘢𝘮 𝘵𝘰 𝘣𝘦𝘩𝘢𝘷𝘦 𝘭𝘪𝘬𝘦 𝘵𝘩𝘢𝘵.”\n\nWe’re actively looking for ways to help clients understand that 𝗰𝘂𝗹𝘁𝘂𝗿𝗲 — 𝗳𝗼𝗿 𝗲𝘅𝗮𝗺𝗽𝗹𝗲, 𝘁𝗵𝗲 𝗮𝗯𝗶𝗹𝗶𝘁𝘆 𝘁𝗼 𝘁𝗿𝗲𝗮𝘁 𝗳𝗲𝗲𝗱𝗯𝗮𝗰𝗸 𝗮𝘀 𝗱𝗮𝘁𝗮 — 𝗰𝗮𝗻 𝗯𝗲𝗰𝗼𝗺𝗲 𝗮 𝗸𝗲𝘆 𝗱𝗿𝗶𝘃𝗲𝗿 𝗼𝗳 𝘀𝘂𝗰𝗰𝗲𝘀𝘀 𝗳𝗼𝗿 𝘁𝗵𝗲 𝗲𝗻𝘁𝗶𝗿𝗲 𝗼𝗿𝗴𝗮𝗻𝗶𝘇𝗮𝘁𝗶𝗼𝗻.\nThis isn’t obvious until you experience it in real life.\n\nSo how do we explain this to clients who’ve never experienced it?\nHow do we help clients feel this culture before they go through it?\n\nIt’s a bit like trying to explain a palm tree to an Inuit who has never seen anything taller than moss.\n\nStill figuring this out.\nIf you’ve cracked the code on explaining the intangible — 𝗜’𝗺 𝗮𝗹𝗹 𝗲𝗮𝗿𝘀.👇",
